   "source": [
    "## 8. Model 1 — Linear Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "Linear Regression is used as a simple interpretable model.  \n",
    "It assumes additive and linear relationships between the predictors and the target."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "id": "55761386",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Linear Regression - Train MAE: 5.539985595611705\n",
      "Linear Regression - Test MAE: 5.589860715251957\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "lr = LinearRegression()\n",
    "lr.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "lr_train_pred = lr.predict(X_train)\n",
    "lr_test_pred = lr.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "lr_train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, lr_train_pred)\n",
    "lr_test_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, lr_test_pred)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Linear Regression - Train MAE:\", lr_train_mae)\n",
    "print(\"Linear Regression - Test MAE:\", lr_test_mae)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e0f86fe5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 9. Model 2 — Random Forest\n",
    "\n",
    "Random Forest can capture nonlinear relationships and interactions between variables.  \n",
    "This is useful in F1 because the effect of grid position and team strength is unlikely to be purely linear."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 38,
   "id": "dc5f461c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Random Forest - Train MAE: 5.323977948444585\n",
      "Random Forest - Test MAE: 5.604109722131201\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "rf = RandomForestRegressor(\n",
    "    n_estimators=200,\n",
    "    max_depth=10,\n",
    "    min_samples_leaf=3,\n",
    "    random_state=RANDOM_SEED\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "rf.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "rf_train_pred = rf.predict(X_train)\n",
    "rf_test_pred = rf.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "rf_train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, rf_train_pred)\n",
    "rf_test_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, rf_test_pred)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Random Forest - Train MAE:\", rf_train_mae)\n",
    "print(\"Random Forest - Test MAE:\", rf_test_mae)"
   ]
